{"key":"processedPost-12397750","value":{"id":12397750,"first":12085159,"last":12410731,"when":1271351840,"utime":"04/15/10 08:17 PM","content":"Cracked corn leaks a lot of starch out, which will lead to a higher incidence of uncolonized areas, thus more contamination.&nbsp; Even popcorn generally has many more bacterial endospores than other grains, leading to a higher rate of bacterial contamination.<br /><br />The 'faster colonization' you see is related to the fact that the mycelium initially only colonizes the surface of the grains, thus a grain with a large surface area seems to colonize faster, but in a given sized jar, you only have a third or less the amount of mycelium you'd have with a smaller grain.&nbsp; In other words, large grains such as corn are inferior when spawned to a bulk substrate.&nbsp; Corn was all the rage a few years ago until people discovered that they can get a higher success ratio with other grains, such as rye berries, which is best.<br />RR","title":"Re: Is the shake really worth it?","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}